<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="195" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,870,1509]" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1051,1077]" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. Kobayashi" authorityYear="1989" box="[324,585,1051,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Platysodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="195" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="formosanus">
<emphasis box="[324,585,1051,1077]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Platysodes formosanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is extremely similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Arrow, M. O. de Lisle" authorityYear="1910" box="[859,970,1051,1076]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Platysodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="195" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jansoni">
<emphasis box="[859,970,1051,1076]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">P. jansoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the parameres of both also show no differences (
<figureCitation box="[291,428,1087,1113]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–17" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1868,1892]" captionTargetBox="[221,1368,275,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-69@4.[213,1374,273,1845]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 9–17. Specimens of Platysodes Westwood, 1873. 9–12, P. formosanus Kobayashi, 1990: 9, female habitus (MYNU); 10–11, slightly greasy male and distal declivity of elytra (CKSJ); 12, parameres of holotype in apical view (MSMT; provided by Yu-Tang Wang). 13–17, P. jansoni Arrow, 1910: 13, greasy female with two maculae on elytron (BPBM; provided by James H. Boone); 14, female habitus (CKSJ); 15–16, male habitus and distal declivity of elytra (MNHN); 17, parameres in apical view (provided by Christophe Rivier). Red arrows emphasize the tomentose maculae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4301819" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4301819/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Figs. 12, 17</figureCitation>
), and that resulted in 
<bibRefCitation author="Qiu, J. Y. &amp; Xu, H. &amp; Chen, L." box="[675,864,1086,1113]" pageId="3" pageNumber="195" pagination="553 - 564" refId="ref4697" refString="Qiu, J. Y., Xu, H. &amp; Chen, L. (2015) Review of the Oriental genus Platysodes Westwood (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Cetoniinae: Cremastocheilini) with a redescription of Platysodes madoni Bourgoin. Zootaxa, 4021 (4), 553 - 564. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4021.4.5" type="journal article" year="2015">
Qiu 
<emphasis box="[724,781,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">et al.</emphasis>
(2015)
</bibRefCitation>
presumed them as the same species. Traditionally, the former is characterized by elytron bearing one tomentose macula and restricted to 
<collectingCountry box="[1139,1298,1123,1149]" name="Taiwan Island" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Taiwan Island</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Kobayashi, H." pageId="3" pageNumber="195" pagination="73 - 81" refId="ref4670" refString="Kobayashi, H. (1990) Four new scarabaeid beetles (Coleoptera, Scarabaeidae) from Taiwan. Elytra, 18, 73 - 81." type="journal article" year="1990">Kobayashi 1990</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Qiu, J. Y. &amp; Xu, H. &amp; Chen, L." box="[222,395,1158,1185]" pageId="3" pageNumber="195" pagination="553 - 564" refId="ref4697" refString="Qiu, J. Y., Xu, H. &amp; Chen, L. (2015) Review of the Oriental genus Platysodes Westwood (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Cetoniinae: Cremastocheilini) with a redescription of Platysodes madoni Bourgoin. Zootaxa, 4021 (4), 553 - 564. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4021.4.5" type="journal article" year="2015">
Qiu 
<emphasis box="[271,328,1159,1185]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
), while the latter is totally black and distributed in eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1051,1109,1159,1185]" name="India" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">India</collectingCountry>
and Indochina (
<bibRefCitation author="Arrow, G. J." box="[1290,1431,1159,1185]" pageId="3" pageNumber="195" refId="ref4632" refString="Arrow, G. J. (1910) The Fauna of British India (Including Ceylon and Burma). Lamellicornia I (Cetoniinae and Dynastinae). Taylor &amp; Francis, London, 322 pp." type="book" year="1910">Arrow 1910</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Qiu, J. Y. &amp; Xu, H. &amp; Chen, L." box="[151,328,1194,1221]" pageId="3" pageNumber="195" pagination="553 - 564" refId="ref4697" refString="Qiu, J. Y., Xu, H. &amp; Chen, L. (2015) Review of the Oriental genus Platysodes Westwood (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Cetoniinae: Cremastocheilini) with a redescription of Platysodes madoni Bourgoin. Zootaxa, 4021 (4), 553 - 564. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4021.4.5" type="journal article" year="2015">
Qiu 
<emphasis box="[201,259,1195,1221]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
). However, we recently obtained a female whose appearance perfectly matches the characteristics of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. Kobayashi" authorityYear="1989" box="[181,339,1231,1257]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Platysodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="195" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="formosanus">
<emphasis box="[181,339,1231,1257]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">P. formosanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[353,421,1231,1257]" captionStart="FIGURES 9–17" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1868,1892]" captionTargetBox="[221,1368,275,1835]" captionTargetId="figure-69@4.[213,1374,273,1845]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 9–17. Specimens of Platysodes Westwood, 1873. 9–12, P. formosanus Kobayashi, 1990: 9, female habitus (MYNU); 10–11, slightly greasy male and distal declivity of elytra (CKSJ); 12, parameres of holotype in apical view (MSMT; provided by Yu-Tang Wang). 13–17, P. jansoni Arrow, 1910: 13, greasy female with two maculae on elytron (BPBM; provided by James H. Boone); 14, female habitus (CKSJ); 15–16, male habitus and distal declivity of elytra (MNHN); 17, parameres in apical view (provided by Christophe Rivier). Red arrows emphasize the tomentose maculae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4301819" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4301819/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
), but it originated from Guangzhou (
<collectingRegion box="[830,965,1231,1257]" country="China" name="Guangdong" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Guangdong</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[976,1045,1231,1258]" name="China" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">China</collectingCountry>
) where located on the southeastern edge of the Asian continent and between the Indochinese Peninsula and 
<collectingCountry box="[973,1131,1267,1293]" name="Taiwan Island" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Taiwan Island</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[1148,1234,1267,1293]" captionStart="FIGURE 28" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1722,1746]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,273,1699]" captionTargetId="figure-61@7.[164,1423,273,1699]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 28. Known distribution of Platysodes Westwood, 1873 species (inset photograph shows the dead specimen of P. ma- doni Bourgoin, 1923 found at Mount Fanjingshan, Guizhou, China, provided by Ka-Chen Ou-Yang). Distribution data take from Qiu et al. (2015) and specimens examined in the present work." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4301825" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4301825/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
). Furthermore, an individual of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="H. Kobayashi" authorityYear="1989" box="[305,465,1303,1329]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Platysodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="195" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="formosanus">
<emphasis box="[305,465,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">P. formosanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
bearing an indistinct macula on elytron (nearly disappeared) was found from 
<collectingCountry box="[1354,1436,1303,1329]" name="Taiwan" pageId="3" pageNumber="195">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
(
